[[sn:Kamo-wake-ikazuchi-no-Kami]]
[[ja:賀茂別雷命]]

{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamo Wake Ikazuchi}}

'''Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto''' (賀茂別雷命) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto is the {{ill|saijin|lt=deity enshrined|ja|祭神|12=draft|12=draft}} at {{ill|Kamo Wakeikazuchi Shrine|ja|賀茂別雷神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (commonly known as Kamigamo Shrine) and is worshipped at various {{ill|Kamo shrines|ja|加茂神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (賀茂神社 or 鴨神社) throughout Japan.

The deity does not appear in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, in the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}} text *Kamo no Honji* (賀茂之本地), Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto is identified with {{ill|Ajisukitakahikone|ja|阿遅鉏高日子根神|12=draft|12=draft}}, a deity mentioned in the *Kojiki*.

An excerpt from the {{ill|Yamashiro no Kuni Fudoki|ja|Yamashiro Province 風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}, a now-lost geographical and mythological record, recounts the following tale about Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto. {{ill|Kamo no Tachi no Tsunomi|ja|賀茂建角身命|12=draft|12=draft}}, the deity of {{ill|Kamo Mioya Shrine|ja|賀茂御祖神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, had a daughter named {{ill|Tama Yori Hime|ja|玉依姫|12=draft|12=draft}} (also enshrined at Kamo Mioya Shrine). While Tama Yori Hime was playing at the Seimi stream of the Ishikawa River (now known as the {{ill|Kamo River (Yodo River system)|ja|鴨川 (淀川水系)|12=draft|12=draft}}), a vermilion-painted arrow drifted down from upstream.

She brought the arrow home and placed it near her bed, which caused her to conceive a child. That child was Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto. Upon reaching adulthood, during a celebration, his grandfather, Kamo no Tachi no Tsunomi, said, "Offer this sake to the one you believe to be your father." At that moment, Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto ascended to the heavens, breaking through the roof, revealing that his father was a divine being. The vermilion-painted arrow was identified as the deity of {{ill|Hinoikazuchi Shrine|ja|向日神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (a fire and thunder deity).

=== Folklore ===
Similar stories of divine birth are found in the *Kojiki* (e.g., {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzu-hime|ja|ヒメタタライスズヒメ|12=draft|12=draft}}) and the *Hata Clan Genealogy* (秦氏本系帳, involving Arewotome and {{ill|Ōyamakui|ja|大山咋神|12=draft|12=draft}}). The latter story is often conflated with the tale of Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto, leading to the belief that his father is {{ill|Ōyamakui|ja|大山咋神|12=draft|12=draft}}, the deity enshrined at {{ill|Matsunoo Taisha|ja|松尾大社|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== See Also ==
