An excerpt from the {{ill|Yamashiro no Kuni Fudoki|ja|Yamashiro Province 風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamashiro no Kuni Fudoki|qq=}}, a now-lost geographical and mythological record, recounts the following tale about Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto. {{ill|Kamotaketsunumi no Mikoto|lt=Kamotaketsunumi no Mikoto|lt=Kamo no Tachi no Tsunomi|ja|賀茂建角身命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo no Tachi no Tsunomi|qq=}}, the deity of {{ill|Kamo Mioya Shrine|ja|賀茂御祖神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Mioya Shrine|qq=}}, had a daughter named {{ill|Tama Yori Hime|ja|玉依姫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tama Yori Hime|qq=}} (also enshrined at Kamo Mioya Shrine). While Tama Yori Hime was playing at the Seimi stream of the Ishikawa River (now known as the {{ill|Kamo River|lt=Kamo River|lt=Kamo River (Yodo River system)|ja|鴨川 (淀川水系)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo River (Yodo River system)|qq=}}), a vermilion-painted arrow drifted down from upstream.
She brought the arrow home and placed it near her bed, which caused her to conceive a child. That child was Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto. Upon reaching adulthood, during a celebration, his grandfather, Kamo no Tachi no Tsunomi, said, "Offer this sake to the one you believe to be your father." At that moment, Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto ascended to the heavens, breaking through the roof, revealing that his father was a divine being. The vermilion-painted arrow was identified as the deity of {{ill|Hinoikazuchi Shrine|ja|向日神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hinoikazuchi Shrine|qq=}} (a fire and thunder deity).
=== Folklore === Similar stories of divine birth are found in the *Kojiki* (e.g., {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmononushi|qq=}} and {{ill|Himetataraisuzu-hime|lt=Himetataraisuzu-hime|lt=Hime Tatara Isuzu-hime|ja|ヒメタタライスズヒメ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzu-hime|qq=}}) and the *Hata Clan Genealogy* (秦氏本系帳, involving Arewotome and {{ill|Ōyamakui|ja|大山咋神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamakui|qq=}}). The latter story is often conflated with the tale of Kamo Wake Ikazuchi no Mikoto, leading to the belief that his father is {{ill|Ōyamakui|ja|大山咋神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamakui|qq=}}, the deity enshrined at {{ill|Matsunoo Taisha|ja|松尾大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsunoo Taisha|qq=}}.
